    </concept>
    <task id="task_ah2_3ph_sdc">
        <title>Execute the Test Profiles</title>
        <taskbody>
            <context id="context_hmk_jph_sdc">
                <p>You can run the Validation Factory tests on any host that has access to the
                    clusters you want to test. Typically, however, you would run the tests on the
                    installation host in one of those clusters. The installation host is where you
                    installed Helm and where you ran the Cloud-Native Router installation for that
                    cluster.</p>
                <p>All clusters must have Cloud-Native Router installed, and all nodes in all
                    clusters must allow the same login credentials (username and password or SSH
                    key).</p>
            </context>
            <steps id="steps_my2_mph_sdc">
                <step>
                    <cmd>Download the Validation Factory software package to the installation host
                        in one of the clusters that you want to test. The installation host is where
                        you have Helm installed and where you ran the Cloud-Native Router
                        installation for that cluster.</cmd>
                    <info>
                        <p>You can download the Cloud-Native Router Validation Factory software
                            package from the Juniper Networks software download site. See <xref href="../ref/jcnr-sw-download-packages.dita"/>.</p>
                    </info>
                </step>
                <step>
                    <cmd>Gunzip and untar the software package.</cmd>
                    <info>
                        <codeblock id="codeblock_p35_sgk_sdc">tar -xzvf JCNR_Validation_Factory_<varname>&lt;release&gt;</varname>.tar.gz</codeblock>
                    </info>
                </step>
                <step>
                    <cmd>Load the provided images on all nodes in the cluster. The images are
                        located in the downloaded package.</cmd>
                    <info>See <xref href="../task/jcnr-deploy-prepackaged-images.dita"/>.</info>
                </step>
                <step id="step_ofq_2lq_xdc">
                    <cmd>If desired, configure the port where you want the test results to be
                        accessible.</cmd>
                    <info>Look for the following line in
                            <filepath>validation-factory/values.yaml</filepath> and change the port
                        number to your desired
                        value:<codeblock id="codeblock_m2y_flk_sdc">nodePort: 30000</codeblock></info>
                </step>
                <step>
                    <cmd>Install the Helm chart.</cmd>
                    <info>
                        <codeblock id="codeblock_d5c_mnj_sdc">cd validation-factory</codeblock>
                        <codeblock id="codeblock_mlr_mnj_sdc">helm install validation-factory .</codeblock>
                    </info>
                </step>
                <step>
                    <cmd>Create a secret with the login credentials and kubeconfigs of your clusters
                        and apply it.</cmd>
                    <info>valfac-secrets.yaml:<codeblock id="codeblock_spb_fdk_sdc">
apiVersion: v1
kind: Secret
metadata:
   name: <varname>&lt;name_of_secret&gt;</varname>
   namespace: jcnr
type: Opaque
data:
   key: <varname>&lt;base64-encoded_ssh_key&gt;</varname>
   username: <varname>&lt;base64-encoded_username&gt;</varname>
   password: <varname>&lt;base64-encoded_password&gt;</varname>
   <varname>&lt;cluster1_name&gt;</varname>-kubeconfig: <varname>&lt;base64-encoded_kubeconfig_of_cluster1&gt;</varname> 
   <varname>&lt;cluster2_name&gt;</varname>-kubeconfig: <varname>&lt;base64-encoded_kubeconfig_of_cluster2&gt;</varname>
   <varname>&lt;clusterN_name&gt;</varname>-kubeconfig: <varname>&lt;base64-encoded_kubeconfig_of_clusterN&gt;</varname>
   etc.</codeblock><dl id="dl_ulm_2fk_sdc">
                            <dlentry>
                                <dt>name</dt>
                                <dd>The name you want to call this secret.</dd>
                            </dlentry>
                            <dlentry>
                                <dt>key</dt>
                                <dd>The base64-encoded ssh key that allows <codeph>username</codeph>
                                    to log in to every node. If you specify the
                                    <codeph>key</codeph>, then you don't specify the
                                        <codeph>password</codeph>.</dd>
                            </dlentry>
                            <dlentry>
                                <dt>username</dt>
                                <dd>The base64-encoded username to log in to every node.</dd>
                            </dlentry>
                            <dlentry>
                                <dt>password</dt>
                                <dd>The base64-encoded password for <codeph>username</codeph> to log
                                    in to every node. If you specify the <codeph>password</codeph>,
                                    then you don't specify the <codeph>key</codeph>.</dd>
                            </dlentry>
                            <dlentry>
                                <dt><varname>&lt;cluster1_name&gt;</varname>-kubeconfig</dt>
                                <dd>The base64-encoded kubeconfig file of the first cluster. The
                                    order that you list your clusters is not important, but
                                        <varname>&lt;cluster1_name&gt;</varname> must match the name of
                                    one of your clusters.</dd>
                            </dlentry>
                            <dlentry>
                                <dt><varname>&lt;cluster2_name&gt;</varname>-kubeconfig</dt>
                                <dd>The base64-encoded kubeconfig file of the second cluster.
                                        <varname>&lt;cluster2_name&gt;</varname> must match the name of
                                    one of the remaining clusters.</dd>
                            </dlentry>
                            <dlentry>
                                <dt><varname>&lt;clusterN_name&gt;</varname>-kubeconfig</dt>
                                <dd>The base64-encoded kubeconfig file of the N<sup>th</sup>
                                    cluster. <varname>&lt;clusterN_name&gt;</varname> must match the
                                    name of one of the remaining clusters.</dd>
                            </dlentry>
                        </dl><note id="note_lmz_thk_sdc">
                            <p>You'll need to base64-encode most of the required information in the
                                secrets manifest.</p>
                            <ul id="ul_o3r_q3k_sdc">
                                <li>
                                    <p>To base64-encode a file: <codeph>base64 -w0
                                                <varname>&lt;file&gt;</varname></codeph></p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>To base64-encode a string: <codeph>echo -n
                                                <varname>&lt;string&gt;</varname> | base64
                                            -w0</codeph></p>
                                    <p>Copy the output to the respective locations in the secrets
                                        manifest.</p>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </note>Apply the
                        secret:<codeblock id="codeblock_ulc_pmk_sdc">kubectl apply -f valfac-secrets.yaml</codeblock></info>
                </step>
                <step>
                    <cmd>Configure the test topology manifest. See <xref href="#concept_ggb_x4h_sdc" format="dita"/>.</cmd>
                </step>
                <step>
                    <cmd>Apply the manifest to begin test execution.</cmd>
                    <info>For
                        example:<codeblock id="codeblock_xmw_r35_ldc">kubectl create -f fivenode_topology_test.yaml</codeblock></info>
                </step>
                <step>
                    <cmd>View the test results.</cmd>
                    <info>
                        <p>View the test results at
                                    <userinput>http://<varname>&lt;cluster_node_IP&gt;</varname>:<varname>&lt;node_port&gt;</varname>/<varname>&lt;test_topology_name&gt;</varname>/<varname>&lt;test_topology_name&gt;</varname>.html</userinput>,
                            where <varname>&lt;node_port&gt;</varname> is the value you set in step
                                <xref href="#task_ah2_3ph_sdc/step_ofq_2lq_xdc"/>.</p>
                        <p>For example, if you executed the test profile named
                                <codeph>fivenode-mplsoverudp</codeph> on a cluster with node IP
                            address <codeph>10.0.0.100</codeph> and node port
                            <codeph>30000</codeph>, you'll be able to see the results at
                                <userinput>http://10.0.0.100:30000/fivenode-mplsoverudp/fivenode-mplsoverudp.html</userinput>.</p>
                    </info>
                </step>
            </steps>
        </taskbody>
    </task>
